alzano]]\n**[[Paschal Baylon]]\n**[[William Hobart Hare]] ([[Episcopal Church (USA)]])\n**[[Restituta]]\n**[[May 17 (Eastern Orthodox liturgics)]]\n*[[Children's Day (Norway)]]\n*[[Constitution Day]] ([[Nauru]])\n*[[Norwegian Constitution Day]]\n*Earliest date on which [[Trinity Sunday]] can fall, while June 20 is the latest; celebrated on the first Sunday after [[Pentecost]]. ([[Western Christianity]])\n*[[Feast of \u2018A\u1e93amat]] ([[Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Faith]])\n*[[Galician Literature Day]] or ''D\u00eda das Letras Galegas'' ([[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]])\n*[[National Day Against Homophobia]] (Canada)\n*[[International Day Against Homophobia, Transphobia and Biphobia]] also known as IDAHOT<ref>https://www.cig.gov.pt/IDAHOT/</ref>\n*[[Liberation Day]] ([[Democratic Republic of the Congo]])\n*[[Navy Day (Argentina)]]\n*[[World Hypertension Day]]\n*[[World Information Society Day]] ([[International observance|International]])\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/may/17 BBC: On This Day]\n* {{NYT On this day|month=05|day=17}}\n* [http://canadachannel.ca/todayincanadianhistory/index.php/May_17 Today in Canadian History]\n\n{{months}}\n\n[[Category:Days of the year]]\n[[Category:May]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-pc1}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{calendar}}\n{{This date in recent years}}\n{{Day}}\n\n==Events==\n*[[1395]] &ndash; [[Battle of Rovine]]: The [[Wallachia]]ns defeat an invading [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] army.<ref>Ostrogorsky, George. ''History of the Byzantine State'', p. 551. Published by Rutgers University Press, 1969. {{ISBN|0-8135-1198-4}}.</ref>\n*[[1536]] &ndash; [[George Boleyn, 2nd Viscount Rochford]] and four other men are executed for treason.\n*  1536   &ndash; [[Henry VIII of England|Henry VIII]] and [[Anne Boleyn]]'s marriage is annulled.\n*[[1590]] &ndash; [[Anne of Denmark]] is crowned [[Queen consort|Queen]] of [[Kingdom of Scotland|Scotland]].\n*[[1642]] &ndash; [[Paul de Chomedey, Sieur de Maisonneuve]] (1612\u20131676) founds the [[Ville Marie de Montr\u00e9al]].\n*[[1673]] &ndash; [[Louis Jolliet]] and [[Jacques Marquette]] begin exploring the [[Mississippi River]].\n*[[1792]] &ndash; The [[New York Stock Exchange]] is formed under the [[Buttonwood Agreement]].\n*[[1805]] &ndash; [[Muhammad Ali of Egypt|Muhammad Ali]] becomes [[W\u0101li]] of [[Egypt]].\n*[[1809]] &ndash; Emperor [[Napoleon|Napoleon I]] orders the annexation of the [[Papal States]] to the [[First French Empire|French Empire]].\n*[[1814]] &ndash; [[Military occupation|Occupation]] of [[Monaco]] changes from French to Austrian.\n*  1814   &ndash; The [[Constitution of Norway]] is signed and [[Crown Prince]] [[Christian VIII of Denmark|Christian Frederick]] of Denmark is elected [[King of Norway]] by the [[Norwegian Constituent Assembly]].\n*[[1859]] &ndash; Members of the [[Melbourne Football Club]] codified the [[Laws of Australian rules football#Melbourne Rules of 1859|first rules]] of [[Australian rules football]].\n*[[1863]] &ndash; [[Rosal\u00eda de Castro]] publishes ''Cantares Gallegos'', the first book in the [[Galician language]].\n*[[1865]] &ndash; The International Telegraph Union (later the [[International Telecommunication Union]]) is established in Paris.\n*[[1869]] &ndash; Imperial [[Empire of Japan|Japanese]] forces defeat the remnants of the [[Tokugawa shogunate]] in the [[Battle of Hakodate]] to end the [[Boshin War]].\n*[[1875]] &ndash; [[Aristides (horse)|Aristides]] wins the first [[Kentucky Derby]].\n*[[1900]] &ndash; [[Second Boer War]]: British troops relieve [[Siege of Mafeking|Mafeking]].\n*  1900   &ndash; The children's novel ''[[The Wonderful Wizard of Oz]]'', by L. Frank Baum, is first published in the United States. The first copy is given to the author's sister.<ref>{{cite book |last= |first= |title=The Wonderful Wizard of Oz By L.Frank Baum With Pictures by W.W. Denslow  |publisher=Geo. M. Hill Co. |year= 1900 |place=Chicago |url=https://archive.org/details/wonderfulwizardo00baumiala |accessdate= February 6, 2018 |via= Internet Archive }}</ref> \n*[[1902]] &ndash; Greek archaeologist [[Valerios Stais]] discovers the [[Antikythera mechanism]], an ancient mechanical [[analog computer]].\n*[[1914]] &ndash; The [[Protocol of Corfu]] is signed, recognising [[Autonomous Republic of Northern Epirus|full autonomy]] to [[Northern Epirus]] under nominal [[Albania]]n sovereignty.\n*[[1915]] &ndash; The last [[The Liberal Party (UK)|British Liberal Party]] government (led by [[H. H. Asquith]]) falls.\n*[[1933]] &ndash; [[Vidkun Quisling]] and [[Johan Bernhard Hjort]] form [[Nasjonal Samling]] &mdash; the [[Nazism|national-socialist]] party of Norway.\n*[[1939]] &ndash; The [[Columbia Lions]] and the [[Princeton Tigers]] play in the United States' first televised sporting event, a [[college baseball|collegiate baseball]] game in New York City.\n*[[1940]] &ndash; [[World War II]]: Germany occupies [[Brussels]], Belgium.\n*[[1943]] &ndash; World War II: [[Dambuster Raids]] commence by [[No. 617 Squadron RAF]].\n*[[1954]] &ndash; The [[United States Supreme Court]] hands down a unanimous decision in ''[[Brown v. Board of Education]] of [[Topeka, Kansas]]''.\n*[[1967]] &ndash; [[Six-Day War]]: [[President of Egypt|President]] [[Gamal Abdel Nasser]] of [[Egypt]] demands dismantling of the peace-keeping [[UN Emergency Force]] in Egypt.\n*[[1969]] &ndash; [[Venera program]]: [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] ''[[Venera 6]]'' begins its descent into the [[atmosphere]] of [[Venus]], sending back atmospheric data before being crushed by pressure.\n*[[1973]] &ndash; [[Watergate scandal]]: Televised hearings begin in the [[United States Senate]].\n*[[1974]] &ndash; [[The Troubles]]: [[Dublin and Monaghan bombings|Thirty-three civilians are killed]] and 300 injured when the [[Ulster Volunteer Force]] (UVF) detonates four car bombs in [[Dublin]] and [[Monaghan]], [[Republic of Ireland]]. \n*  1974   &ndash; [[Los Angeles Police Department|Police in Los Angeles]] raid the [[Symbionese Liberation Army]]'s headquarters, killing six members, including [[Camilla Hall]].\n*[[1977]] &ndash; [[Nolan Bushnell]] opened the first [[Chuck E. Cheese's]] in [[San Jose, California]].\n*[[1980]] &ndash; General [[Chun Doo-hwan]] of South Korea [[Coup d'\u00e9tat of May Seventeenth|seizes control]] of the government and declares [[martial law]] in order to suppress student demonstrations.\n*  1980   &ndash; On the eve of presidential elections, [[Maoism|Maoist]] [[guerrilla warfare|guerrilla]] group [[Shining Path]] attacks a polling location in [[Chuschi]] (a town in [[Ayacucho]]), starting the [[Internal conflict in Peru]].\n*[[1983]] &ndash; The [[United States Department of Energy|U.S. Department of Energy]] declassifies documents showing world's largest [[Mercury (element)|mercury]] pollution event in [[Oak Ridge, Tennessee]] (ultimately found to be 4.2 million pounds), in response to the ''Appalachian Observer'''s [[Freedom of Information Act (United States)|Freedom of Information Act]] request.\n*  1983   &ndash; [[Lebanon]], [[Israel]], and the United States sign an [[May 17 Agreement|agreement]] on Israeli withdrawal from [[Lebanon]].\n*[[1984]] &ndash; [[Charles, Prince of Wales|Prince Charles]] calls a proposed addition to the [[National Gallery]], London, a \"monstrous carbuncle on the face of a much-loved and elegant friend\", sparking controversies on the proper role of the [[British Royal Family|Royal Family]] and the course of [[modern architecture]].\n*[[1987]] &ndash; [[Iran\u2013Iraq War]]: An [[Ba'athist Iraq|Iraq]]i [[Dassault Mirage F1]] fighter jet [[USS Stark incident|fires two missiles]] into the U.S. Navy warship {{USS|Stark|FFG-31|6}}, killing 37 and injuring 21 of her crew.\n*[[1990]] &ndash; The General Assembly of the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) eliminates [[homosexuality]] from the list of psychiatric diseases.\n*[[1992]] &ndash; Three days of [[Black May (1992)|popular protests]] against the government of [[Prime Minister of Thailand]] [[Suchinda Kraprayoon]] begin in [[Bangkok]], leading to a military crackdown that results in 52 officially confirmed deaths, hundreds of injuries, many disappearances, and more than 3,500 arrests.\n*[[1994]] &ndash; [[Malawi]] holds its [[Malawian general election, 1994|first multi-party elections]].\n*[[1995]] &ndash; [[Shawn Nelson (American rampager)|Shawn Nelson]] steals an [[M60 Patton|M60 tank]] from the [[California Army National Guard]] [[armory (military)|Armory]] in [[San Diego]] and proceeds to go on a rampage.\n*[[1997]] &ndash; Troops of [[Laurent Kabila]] march into [[Kinshasa]]. [[Zaire]] is officially renamed [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]].\n*[[2000]] &ndash; [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] and [[Galatasaray S.K. (football)|Galatasaray]] fans clash in the [[2000 UEFA Cup Final riots]] in Copenhagen\n*[[2004]] &ndash; The first legal [[same-sex marriage]]s in the U.S. are performed in the state of [[Same-sex marriage in Massachusetts#First same-sex marriages|Massachusetts]].\n*[[2006]] &ndash; The aircraft carrier {{USS|Oriskany|CV-34|6}} is sunk in the [[Gulf of Mexico]] as an [[artificial reef]].\n*[[2007]] &ndash; Trains from [[North Korea|North]] and South Korea cross the [[38th parallel north|38th Parallel]] in a test-run agreed by both governments. This is the first time that trains have crossed the Demilitarized Zone since [[1953]].\n*[[2014]] &ndash; A [[2014 Lao People's Liberation Army Air Force An-74 crash|plane crash]] in northern [[Laos]] kills 17 people.\n\n==Births==\n<!-- Please do not add yourself or people without Wikipedia articles to this list. No red links, please. Do not link multiple occurrences of the same year, just link the first occurrence. Do not trust \"this year in history\" websites for accurate date information. -->\n*[[1155]] &ndash; [[Jien]], Japanese monk, poet, and historian (d. 1225)\n*[[1443]] &ndash; [[Edmund, Earl of Rutland]] (d. 1460)\n*[[1451]] &ndash; [[Engelbert II of Nassau]], Count of Nassau-Vianden and Lord of Breda (1475\u20131504) (d. 1504)\n*[[1490]] &ndash; [[Albert, Duke of Prussia]], last Grand Master of the Teutonic Knights (d. 1568)\n*[[1500]] &ndash; [[Federico II Gonzaga, Duke of Mantua]] (d. 1540)\n*[[1551]] &ndash; [[Martin Delrio]], Belgian occultist and theologian (d. 1601)\n*[[1568]] &ndash; [[Anna Vasa of Sweden]], Swedish princess (d. 1625)\n*[[1610]] &ndash; [[Stefano della Bella]], Italian engraver and etcher (d. 1664)<ref>[[Dearborn-Massar|Massar, Phyllis Dearborn]] (1996). \"Bella, Stefano della\", vol. 3, pp. 631\u2013634, in ''[[The Dictionary of Art]]'' (34 vols.), edited by Jane Turner. New York: Grove. {{ISBN|9781884446009}}. Also at [[Oxford Art Online]], [http://www.oxfordartonline.com/subscriber/article/grove/art/T007589 subscription required] (accessed 22 November 2010)</ref>\n*[[1628]] &ndash; [[Ferdinand Charles, Archduke of Austria]] (d. 1662)\n*[[1636]] &ndash; [[Edward Colman]], English Catholic courtier under Charles II (d. 1678)\n*[[1682]] &ndash; [[Bartholomew Roberts]], Welsh pirate (d. 1722)\n*[[1698]] &ndash; [[Gio Nicola Buhagiar]], Maltese painter (d. 1752)<ref>{{cite book|last1=Schiavone|first1=Michael J.|title=Dictionary of Maltese Biographies Vol. 1 A\u2013F|date=2009|publisher=Pubblikazzjonijiet Indipendenza|location=[[Piet\u00e0, Malta|Piet\u00e0]]|isbn=9789993291329|pages=339\u2013340}}</ref>\n*[[1706]] &ndash; [[Andreas Felix von Oefele]], German historian and librarian (d. 1780)\n*[[1718]] &ndash; [[Robert Darcy, 4th Earl of Holderness]], English politician and diplomat, [[Secretary of State for the Southern Department]] (d. 1778)\n*[[1732]] &ndash; [[Francesco Pasquale Ricci]], Italian violinist and composer (d. 1817)\n*[[1743]] &ndash; [[Seth Warner]], American colonel (d. 1784)\n*[[1749]] &ndash; [[Edward Jenner]], English physician and microbiologist (d. 1823)\n*[[1758]] &ndash; [[Sir John St Aubyn, 5th Baronet]], English politician (d. 1839)\n*[